Description: Small complete seal-impression made of fine brown Nile clay that was hardened after excavation and shows darker discolouration. The rear shows a slightly concave surface, maybe from a leather bag. One deep impression of a turned cord with a width of 0.25cm is impressed in the rear. The upper side convex and bends downwards to the sides. Two impressions of the same oval scarab-like seal directly parallel and next to each other are preserved with finger impressions around it and partly covering the impression as well. Visible are three columnsof hieroglyphs with a cartouche in the middle, from left to right: 1) nTr nfr nb tAwi 2) (MAa.t-kA-R')| nbw (Gardiner S12) 3) jTj(?)-HD (T25). 1) the good god, the lord of the two Lands 2) Hatshepsut 3) who takes the white crown(?). The same motif can be found on EA86815 where it is even clearer.
Acquisition notes: Formerly housed by the Birmingham Museum and Art Gallery and the EES London.
